SYNONYM 

   ðŸ”¹ In Oracle, a synonym is also called as Database Object
   ðŸ”¹ A synonym is an alias or alternative name for a database object, such as a table, view, sequence, or stored procedure
   ðŸ”¹ It allowing users to access these objects without  knowing  the exact object name or schema. 
   ðŸ”¹ Synonyms are often used for security

Types of Synonyms

    ðŸ”¹ Private Synonym
            -> Created for use by a specific user.
            -> Accessible only within the userâ€™s schema.

    ðŸ”¹ Public Synonym

            -> Created for use by all users in the database.
            -> Requires CREATE PUBLIC SYNONYM system privilege.

syntax:

    CREATE [PUBLIC] SYNONYM synonym_name 
    FOR [schema.]object_name;

Example

    Private Synonym
    ----------------

    -- Suppose a table exists in SCOTT schema

        CREATE SYNONYM emp_table FOR scott.emp;

    -- Now you can access employees table directly as:

        SELECT * FROM emp_table;


    Public Synonym
    ---------------

    -- Creating synonym accessible by all users
       
       CREATE PUBLIC SYNONYM EMPLOYEE_table FOR scott.EMP;

    -- Any user can now query:

       SELECT * FROM EMPLOYEE_table;


    Dropping a Synonym:
    -------------------

    SYNTAX :

        DROP [PUBLIC] SYNONYM synonym_name;

    EXAMPLE :

        DROP  SYNONYM emp_table ;

        DROP PUBLIC SYNONYM EMPLOYEE_table;

    Check your own synonyms
    ------------------------

    SELECT synonym_name, table_owner, table_name
    FROM user_synonyms;

    Check other usersâ€™ synonyms (accessible to you)
    ------------------------------------------------

    SELECT owner, synonym_name, table_owner, table_name
    FROM all_synonyms
    WHERE owner = 'USER_NAME';
